=3D"center"><td>4</td></tr></tbody></table></td>
</tr></tbody></table>

<p>When exponents are raised to another exponent, the exponents are multipl=
ied.</p>
<p align=3D"center">
		(a<sup>m</sup>)<sup>n</sup> =3D a<sup>(m =C3=97 n)</sup><br>
	EX:	 (2<sup>2</sup>)<sup>4</sup> =3D 4<sup>4</sup> =3D 256<br>
		(2<sup>2</sup>)<sup>4</sup> =3D 2<sup>(2 =C3=97 4)</sup> =3D 2<sup>8</sup=
> =3D 256
</p>

<p>When multiplied bases are raised to an exponent, the exponent is distrib=
uted to both bases.</p>
<p align=3D"center">
		(a =C3=97 b)<sup>n</sup> =3D a<sup>n</sup> =C3=97 b<sup>n</sup><br>

	EX:	 (2 =C3=97 4)<sup>2</sup> =3D 8<sup>2</sup> =3D 64<br>
		(2 =C3=97 4)<sup>2</sup> =3D 2<sup>2</sup> =C3=97 4<sup>2</sup> =3D 4 =C3=
=97 16 =3D 64
</p>

<p>Similarly, when divided bases are raised to an exponent, the exponent is=
 distributed to both bases.</p>

